<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rabin on Next 2 Years in Office; Favored in Poll </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rabin on Next 2 Years in Office; Favored in Poll </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA2506102794 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 0700 GMT 25 
Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA2506102794 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Speaking to our correspondents yesterday, Prime 
Minister Yitzhaq Rabin said that in the coming two years, the 
government will focus on economic and education issues. He 
noted that one of the goals his government has so far failed to 
achieve is keeping inflation under 10-percent. 
  According to him, the fact that the government has served 
half its term does not change anything with regard to the peace 
moves. Mr. Rabin is determined to complete his term, even with a 
minority government. The prime minister was reacting to a 
public opinion poll conducted by the statistics department of 
Haifa University on the occasion of the government completing a 
two-year term. 
  Those polled gave the Rabin government a performance grade 
of 
5.3 on a scale of 10. Some 29 percent of those polled view 
Rabin as their preferred candidate for prime minister, 14 
percent favor Netanyahu, 8 percent chose Shim'on Peres, and 
Hayim Ramon and Ari'el Sharon each won the support of 4 percent. 
The poll surveyed 650 people. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

