<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rabin Says Economy in `Excellent Shape' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rabin Says Economy in `Excellent Shape' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA2406180794 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 1600 GMT 24 
Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA2406180794 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin said that as long as 
he is prime minister no tax will be imposed on stock market 
profits. I opposed such a move in the past, and I still oppose 
it, Rabin said. The prime minister reiterated that the stock 
market does not reflect the economy, which is growing. The 
stock exchange is not a casino but an institute for calculated 
investments. Our Tel Aviv economic correspondent Ya'ir Fiedel 
reports that Rabin said the economy is generally in excellent 
shape, except for certain areas, such as inflation and housing 
prices, which require pinpointed treatment. Rabin was addressing 
business leaders. 

</TEXT>

