<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Air Force Pilots Fly MiG-29, Report Conclusions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Air Force Pilots Fly MiG-29, Report Conclusions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA2806074294 Tel Aviv IDF Radio in Hebrew 0500 GMT 28 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA2806074294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv IDF Radio </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Army affairs correspondent Yariv Ben-Yehuda] </F>
  [Text] A dream came true for four Israeli pilots, 
including Brigadier General D., head of an Air Force division: 
They flew an enemy aircraft. The flights took place in an East 
European country about six months ago, BIT'ON HEYL HA'AVIR 
reveals in this week's issue. The pilots flew the MiG-29 -- 
the Arab countries' most advanced aircraft -- four times, with 
each flight lasting approximately 20 minutes at a temperature 
under 0 degrees centigrade. 
  This unique opportunity to inspect the plane yielded several 
distinct conclusions. According to one of the pilots, the 
MiG-29 is easy to operate and maneuver and is energetic and well 
equipped. It has excellent radar, a very advanced detection 
system, and a more sophisticated throttle than that of the F-16. 
As for its aerodynamic performance, it definitely belongs to 
the state-of-the- art aircraft in the category of the F-15 and 
F-16. 
  The most important conclusion for us: The MiG-29 is 
incapable of reaching Israeli borders from either Iraq or Iran, 
although it certainly can pose a threat to Israeli aircraft 
attempting to reach those countries. The Air Force division 
head summed up: We have a clear advantage over this aircraft, 
but if we are forced to confront it, we may run a certain risk. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

