<F P=100> SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Afghanistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Seen Making Progress Against Militia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Seen Making Progress Against Militia </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Dostam Jet Bombs Civilians </H4>

<F P=102> BK2706063994 Hong Kong AFP in English 0602 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> BK2706063994 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Terence White] </F>
  [Text] Kabul, June 27 (AFP) -- At least 10 people were 
killed or wounded when a jet loyal to the ex-communist Uzbek 
General 'Abdol Rashid Dostam bombed an east Kabul residential 
area early Monday [27 June], witnesses said. 
  The plane dropped between four and six bombs shortly before 
9:00 am (0430 GMT), hitting civilian homes, the witnesses said. 
  "I was sitting down playing cards when suddenly there was a 
huge flash and an explosion," Mohammad Karim told AFP. Karim, 
an ex-military serviceman, who still had blood on his hands from 
digging out the dismembered corpse of one victim, said he 
thought most of the bombs dropped were in the 250-kilogram (550 
pounds) range, but possibly there was one 500-kilogram (1,100 
pound) monster. 
  In one house locals dug with shovels to rescue a man buried 
alive, then turned their attention to another house where two 
children were said to be under the rubble. Hysterical women 
from the bombed houses cried in the street as neighbours were 
packed belongings in taxis to flee the scene. [sentence as 
received] The final casualty toll will not be known until all 
the wreckage has been cleared from the bombed area. 
  The bombing may have been in retaliation for the loss of two 
strategic posts in eastern Kabul at the weekend when forces 
loyal to Afghan President Borhanoddin Rabbani captured Bala 
Hesar and Maranjan Hill from the coalition alliance of Dostam 
and Prime Minister Golboddin Hekmatyar. 
  Meanwhile the rival factions in the east of the city 
continued to trade heavy artillery fire all morning. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

