Daily Report 
<DATE1>  27 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   Saudi Arms for Yemen Said Found in Egyptian Boats </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Saudi Arms for Yemen Said Found in Egyptian Boats </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2706190894 Paris AFP in English 1625 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2706190894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, June 27 (AFP) -- The US navy recently 
discovered two Egyptian ships in the Red Sea carrying Saudi 
weapons to south Yemen, an Egyptian journalist has charged. 
Muhammad Hasanayn Haykal said in a lecture at Cairo University: 
"The US navy in the Red Sea recently intercepted and 
requisitioned two Egyptian boats transporting Saudi arms to 
south Yemen." 
  AFP obtained Monday [27 June] a copy of Haykal's lecture, 
given Wednesday 22 June]. But the US naval command centre based 
in Florida, covering the Middle East, told AFP they were unaware 
of any incident and had not received any internal report on the 
matter. Haykal was close to former Egyptian President Jamal 
'Abd al-Nasir, and has many Arab and western contacts. 
  An Egyptian source, who asked not to be named, said he could 
not confirm or deny the claim. "Egypt's position in principle is 
not to contribute to any effort to supply arms to either of the 
Yemeni parties," he said. 
  Opposition newspaper AL-'ARABI said Monday the two boats 
intercepted by the US navy returned to Egypt with their cargo. 
  Egypt's President Husni Mubarak recently criticised northern 
Yemeni President 'Ali 'Abdallah Salih for his "insistence" on 
trying to maintain unity, saying it could not be achieved by 
force. But Cairo has not recognised the breakaway Yemen 
Democratic Republic, declared by the south on May 21. 
  War broke out between Salih's forces and those of his 
southern rival 'Ali Salim al-Bid on May 5. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

