<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-124 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  28 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   Paper Criticizes Sanaa Rejection of Mediation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Paper Criticizes Sanaa Rejection of Mediation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2806074294 Cairo MENA in Arabic 0608 GMT 28 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2806074294 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 28 Jun (MENA)--AL-AKHBAR says the leaders of 
Yemen have become the Serbian leaders' primary competitors for 
record cease-fire announcements that only end in more vicious 
fighting. 
  But the Yemeni leaders stand out for using the daily 
cease-fire violations to kill as many of their own innocent 
civilians as possible and to destroy the facilities and 
installations for which the Yemeni people have paid huge amounts 
of money, the paper says in its editorial today. 
  It says the arrogant and intransigent positions of some 
Yemeni leaders and their rejection of any Arab mediation will 
not solve the problem. Indeed they will make things worse, 
deepen the wounds, and make it more difficult--if not 
impossible--for things to return to normal. 
  AL-AKHBAR notes extensive Arab diplomatic activity to end 
the 
conflict and asks why the Sanaa government is sending envoys at 
the same time as it rejects Arab mediation as interference in 
its internal affairs. 
  The paper expresses the fear that the Yemeni crisis may be 
internationalized given that some non-Arab quarters are 
exploiting it. This will only make things worse, it says. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

