<F P=100> Libya </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mubarak Holds Extended Talks With al-Qadhdhafi </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Mubarak Holds Extended Talks With al-Qadhdhafi </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Further on al-Qadhdhafi-Mubarak Talks </H4>

<F P=102> LD2706135594 Tripoli Great Jamahiriyah Radio Network in 
Arabic 1230 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2706135594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tripoli Great Jamahiriyah Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] An extended round of talks was held today 
between the brother leader of the revolution [al-Qadhdhafi] and 
Egyptian President Husni Mubarak. The meeting was attended by 
brothers secretary for the General People's Committee, the 
secretary for the People's Bureau for Foreign Liaison and 
International Cooperation, and the ministerial delegation 
accompanying President Mubarak. 
  The talks dealt with bilateral cooperation between the two 
brotherly countries, and Arab and international issues of mutual 
interest. [passage omitted] 
  Egyptian President Husni Mubarak later left Surt today at 
the 
end of this visit to the Great Jamahiriyah. The brother leader 
of the revolution was at the head of those saying farewell to 
President Husni Mubarak at Khalij Surt's civilian airport. 
[passage omitted] 
  President Mubarak made a statement to JANA's correspondent 
before departure. He said: My visits to the Great Jamahiriyah 
are continuous and have a positive effect on the Arab people in 
Egypt and Libya. Our meeting as brothers gives us the 
opportunity to exchange views in Arab, international, and 
bilateral issues. 
  He indicated that all these topics were discussed during the 
meeting. 
  Concerning the Great Jamahiriyah's absence from a meeting of 
Mediterranean basin countries due to be held in Cairo next week, 
President Husni Mubarak said that a restricted preparatory 
committee meeting will be held, and not all Mediterranean basin 
countries will participate. It will prepare a conference, draw 
up an agenda, and specify topics for discussion and when and who 
will take part. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-38114 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes124_d_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-124 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  27 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Libya </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mubarak Holds Extended Talks With al-Qadhdhafi </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Mubarak Holds Extended Talks With al-Qadhdhafi </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Egyptian Foreign Ministry Hails Visit </H4>

<F P=102> LD2706153894 Tripoli JANA in English 1427 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2706153894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tripoli JANA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tripoli, Al Sayf [June] 27 JAMAHIRIYAH NEWS AGENCY 
-- Naji al-Ghatrayfi, the official spokesperson for the Egyptian 
Foreign Ministry described President Husni Mubarak's visit to 
the Great Jamahiriya demonstrated the depth of the relationship 
between the leader of the revolution and the Egyptian president. 
He said that the presence of President Husni Mubarak on the 
land of the Great Jamahiriyah at this time emphasises Egypt's 
solidarity with the great Jamahiriyah and at the same time was a 
[words indistinct] complete solidarity with the Libyan people 
against the background of the unjust measures which the Great 
Jamahiriyah is being subjected to through the so called 
Lockerbie crisis. 
  In a statement to the JAMAHIRIYAH NEWS AGENCY's 
correspondent 
in Cairo, the spokesperson said that this visit reflects the 
care which the two countries sare giving to the process of 
co-ordination and consultation between them in the sphere of 
common interests in the Arab and international arena. 
  He added that Libyan-Egyptian relations were blossoming 
uninterruptedly and he applauded the unique relationship between 
President Husni Mubarak of Egypt and his brother, Col. Mu'ammar 
Al-Qadhdhafi saying that their talks were not limited to simply 
the relationship between the two countries but also to the 
current Arab situation and the strengthening of joint Arab 
action for the benfit of the Great Jamahiriyah and Egypt but 
also for the entire Arab nation. [sentence as received] 

</TEXT>

