<F P=100> IRAQ </F>
<H3> <TI>   Oil Minister Rejects Pipeline Agreement Amendments </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Oil Minister Rejects Pipeline Agreement Amendments </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN2706115494 Amman AL-RA'Y in Arabic 27 Jun 94 p 13 </F>
<F P=103> JN2706115494 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman AL-RA'Y </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Exclusive" report] </F>
  [Text] Baghdad--Iraq has emphasized its rejection of any 
terms or amendments to the Iraqi-Turkish agreement on operating 
the Iraqi oil pipeline crossing Turkish territory under any 
pretext. 
  Iraqi Oil Minister Dr. Safa' Hadi Jawad said that 
maintaining 
this pipeline should be done directly by the two sides. He 
asserted that Turkey should begin implementation of this 
agreement without consultation with the UN Security Council. 
The minister pointed out that the Iraqi-Turkish agreement on 
cleaning and maintaining the pipeline is not based on commercial 
considerations, asserting that the agreement was signed within a 
purely technical framework in order to maintain the pipeline 
which is liable to erosion and damage due to the Iraqi oil 
retained in it since early August 1990. 
  The Iraqi minister said that Iraq and Turkey agreed to use 
part of the revenues of the oil contained in the pipeline to 
repay some debts which Iraq owes Turkey and to use the other 
part of the revenues to purchase food commodities, baby milk, 
and medical and pharmaceutical supplies from Turkish sources. 
The international resolutions do not ban Iraq from importing 
these items. In practice, however, they obstruct their 
importation because the Iraqi assets abroad are still frozen and 
Iraq is prevented from exporting its oil freely. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-38125 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes124_k_94006" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-124 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  27 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> IRAQ </F>
<H3> <TI>   Interviewed on Export Capacity </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Interviewed on Export Capacity </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2706113694 Paris AFP in English 1035 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2706113694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Nicosia, June 27 (AFP)--Iraq now has the capacity to 
export more than two million barrels per day (bpd) of crude oil, 
its oil minister Dr. Safa' Hadi Jawad said in an interview 
published here on Monday. 
  Iraq will also demand an output quota "at parity with Iran," 
currently 3.6 million bpd, from the Organisation of Petroleum 
Exporting Countries (OPEC) when UN sanctions are lifted, Jawad 
told the MIDDLE EAST ECONOMIC SURVEY (MEES). 
  A United Nations embargo on Iraqi oil exports was imposed 
following Iraq's invasion of Kuwait in August 1990. Iraq's 
production quota was set at the same level with Iran's quota in 
July 1990. 
  Jawad said Iraq had met UN resolutions to destroy its 
weapons 
of mass destruction, the condition for the lifting of the 
embargo. 
  "We feel that we will soon return to the market," Jawad told 
the specialist newsletter published in Cyprus during an 
interview in Vienna. 
  "We can export more than 2 million bpd now. The export 
outlets are ready. We sustained heavy damage, but we have 
repaired around 90 per cent of the damaged facilities," he added. 
  Jawad said Iraq could export between 1.2 and 1.3 million bpd 
through the Iraqi-Turkish pipeline, which has a capacity of 1.8 
million bpd, and 1.2 million bpd through the Mina' al-Bakr 
export terminal on the Gulf. 
  Repairs on the nearby Khawr al-Amaya terminal would be ready 
in the next few months to provide an initial export capacity of 
600,000 bpd, al-Habubi said. 
  "We can also resort to exporting by trucks through Turkey 
and 
Jordan, as we did during the eighties. Hence the fact that we 
cannot use the Iraqi-Saudi pipeline will not affect our export 
capacity during the initial export stage." 
  The minister said Iraqi officials have visited Italy, 
Ukraine 
and France recently to discuss joint oil projects, but said 
there had been no negotiations yet with Japanese firms. 
  Jawad said Iraq would "give priority to those companies 
which 
have held negotiations with us during the embargo," after 
sanctions were lifted. 
  Iraq discussed with Ukraine the construction of a spur line 
from the Iraqi-Turkish pipeline to Turkey's Black Sea coast, 
from where oil could be exported to the Ukraine. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-38126 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes124_k_94007" </HT>


