<H3> <TI>   Doctors Urged To Use Fixed Examination Charges </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Doctors Urged To Use Fixed Examination Charges </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN2706200594 Baghdad AL-JUMHURIYAH in Arabic 21 Jun 94 p 5 </F>
<F P=103> JN2706200594 </F>
<F P=104>  Baghdad AL-JUMHURIYAH </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Article By Salah al-'Abd and Nabil al-Wadi] </F>
  [Excerpt] The Doctors Union has issued new instructions 
fixing the charges of medical examinations in private clinics. 
These instructions urge all doctors to comply with the new 
charges, which range from 50 to 100 dinars for a specialized 
doctor and from 25 to 50 dinars for a practitioner. 
  Dr. Nayif al-Hassuni, head of the Doctors Union, said that 
these measures by the union came at the instructions of the 
Council of Ministers to ease the burdens of the citizens. 
  The newspaper AL-JUMHURIYAH has followed the issue of 
charges 
for medical examinations in private clinics and noticed that 
these charges rose in conflict with the citizens' standard of 
living, especially for employees with low incomes. In a number 
of cases, these charges exceeded 500 dinars, when it used to be 
only 10 dinars. The paper also noticed that the rise in the 
charges is due to imposing additional charges, including charges 
for testing blood pressure, diabetes, and cardiography. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

