<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kuwaiti Minister Rejects Attacks Over GCC Yemen Stance </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kuwaiti Minister Rejects Attacks Over GCC Yemen Stance </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2506093894 Kuwait KUNA in Arabic 0804 GMT 25 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2506093894 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuwait KUNA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Kuwait, 25 Jun -- In a press statement published 
here today, Sabah al-Ahmad al-Jabir Al Sabah, first deputy prime 
minister and minister of foreign affairs, stressed the rejection 
of any threats or accusations made against the Gulf Cooperation 
Council [GCC] because of support for the secessionist Yemeni 
state, or that it supported one side at the expense of the other. 
  In a statement to the newspaper AL-ANBA, Shaykh Sabah 
al-Ahmad expressed regret over the Yemeni president's attack on 
GCC states because of the GCC's statement in which it supported 
the UN Security Council resolution, saying that this attack was 
a hard to forgive mistake. 
  Shaykh Sabah al-Ahmad affirmed that all Damascus Declaration 
states were awaiting the current international move aimed at 
resolving the Yemeni crisis and the outcome of the efforts of 
the UN envoy regarding this crisis. He said that these states 
were also awaiting the results the envoy had achieved, which he 
would present to the UN secretary general and the Security 
Council. 
  In light of these results, Shaykh Sabah al-Ahmad added that 
developments and their required resolutions could be discussed 
during the meeting of the Damascus Declaration's foreign 
ministers to be held in Kuwait on 27 June. 

</TEXT>

