<F P=100> Libya </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mubarak Holds Extended Talks With al-Qadhdhafi </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Mubarak Holds Extended Talks With al-Qadhdhafi </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Focus of Talks Detailed </H4>

<F P=102> LD2706214794 Tripoli Libyan Television Network in Arabic 
1930 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2706214794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tripoli Libyan Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Another round of extended talks was held this 
morning between the brother leader of the revolution and 
Egyptian President Husni Mubarak. [passage omitted] 
  JANA's correspondent in Sirte has reported that all aspects 
of bilateral cooperation between the two fraternal countries as 
well as other Arab and international topics of mutual interests 
were reviewed at this round of talks. 
  He added that the meeting also dealt with the situation in 
Yemen and the Egypt's role, which ought to protect Yemeni unity 
and face up to the colonialist schemes aimed at creating schism 
and weakening the Arab nation, beginning with Yemen and followed 
by Saudi Arabia, Egypt, Syria, and the rest of Arab countries. 
In this respect, Egypt's leading role in the Arab homeland and 
in the world, given Egypt's weight, civilization, and huge 
sacrifices for Yemen in the sixties, was stressed. 
  As for Egypt's pan-Arab role, it was reiterated that the 
Israeli schemes were aiming at harming Egypt, because the 
program of the Zionist movement was aimed at establishing the 
so-called state of Israel from the Nile to the Euphrates. 
  As far as the Lockerbie problem was concerned, it was 
asserted that concocting such a problem was aimed at keeping 
Egypt busy with secondary issues and distracting it from playing 
its pan-Arab role. 

</TEXT>

