<DOCNO> FBIS4-38153 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes124_v_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-124 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  26 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Pakistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chambers of Commerce Members Strike Over Budget </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chambers of Commerce Members Strike Over Budget </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Commerce Minister Comments </H4>

<F P=102> BK2606115594 Islamabad Radio Pakistan Overseas Service in 
English 0800 GMT 26 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2606115594 </F>
<F P=104>  Islamabad Radio Pakistan Overseas Service </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A strike is being observed today in some parts of 
country at the call of the Federation of Pakistan Chambers of 
Commerce and Industry [FPCCI] against nonacceptance of their 
budget proposals by the government. In Karachi, industrial 
units and main shopping centers are closed. However, public 
transport and private vehicles are plying as usual. Most of the 
main shopping centers and markets in Islamabad, Rawalpindi, and 
Peshawar are closed. 
  However, the minister for commerce speaking in the National 
Assembly said a number of factories in Sialkot, Naushahra, 
Gujrat, and Sindh are not observing the strike. The minister 
for commerce, Chaudhary Ahmad Mukhtar, has again asked the 
Federation of Pakistan Chambers of Commerce and Industry to call 
off the strike and resume talks with the government about their 
demands. Replying to a point of order by Haji Mohammad Nawaz 
Khokar in the National Assembly today, the commerce minister 
said that the government during talks with representatives of 
FPCCI wanted to evolve some package. However, they continued 
their threatening posture saying that if their demands were not 
accepted, they would go on strike. He said they wanted taxation 
rules and laws of their choice and were trying to dictate to the 
government. He said there were some politically motivated 
people who raised slogans and misbehaved during the talks. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

