<F P=100> Pakistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chambers of Commerce Members Strike Over Budget </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chambers of Commerce Members Strike Over Budget </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Strike Enters Second Day </H4>

<F P=102> BK2706155694 Islamabad PTV Television Network in English 
1400 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2706155694 </F>
<F P=104>  Islamabad PTV Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Partial strike by the business community continued 
throughout the country for the second day today. The call for 
the strike was given by the Pakistan Federation of Chambers of 
Commerce and Industry to protest against certain taxation 
proposals in the federal budget. Our correspondents from major 
cities and towns say that as compared to yesterday, most of 
small traders today carried out their business. The impact of 
strike was however witnessed in major shopping centers, big 
business establishments, commercial houses, and industrial 
estates. Our representatives say most of small traders opened 
their premises in the morning, but under pressure from chamber's 
representatives they pulled down their shutters later in the 
day. Like yesterday, transporters and petroleum dealers 
remained averse to the strike call and carried on their normal 
activities. Fruit and vegetable markets remained open and 
normal rush of buyers was visible. The life was normal as 
strike did not affect the common man who was least concerned by 
the shutdown in the major markets and shopping centers. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

