<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Olmert: 'Arafat Has Right To Visit `in Principle' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Olmert: 'Arafat Has Right To Visit `in Principle' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA2806165294 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 1600 GMT 28 
Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA2806165294 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Jerusalem Mayor Ehud Olmert says he accepts that 
Yasir 'Arafat in principle has the right to visit Jerusalem, but 
he objects to such a visit because of 'Arafat's role and for 
fear that it might cause unnecessary friction between Jews and 
Arabs. The mayor of Jerusalem believes that 'Arafat would not 
be coming to pray, but to make declarations. Our correspondent 
Aviv Bushinsky reports that Olmert made these remarks in a 
special meeting with Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin. Mr. Rabin 
summoned the meeting following complaints about a lack of 
communication between him and the mayor. The two men agreed to 
go on meeting in the future to promote various issues, including 
the development of the city. 
  In a meeting of the Knesset Foreign Affairs and Defense 
Committee earlier today, Rabin said that the government was 
looking for every possible way to expand the Jewish population 
of Jerusalem. However, Rabin noted, it is difficult to locate 
land and the government is awaiting the High Court of Justice 
ruling on the issue. 
  Meanwhile, Jerusalem Municipality sources told our 
correspondent that they have been holding legal deliberations 
with regard to illegally built houses in East Jerusalem and 
their possible demolition. The sources noted that two such 
houses in East Jerusalem, over which legal proceedings were 
completed, were demolished in the last two days. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

