<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Peres Proposes Membership in Partnership for Peace </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Peres Proposes Membership in Partnership for Peace </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA2806110194 Tel Aviv HA'ARETZ in Hebrew 28 Jun 94 p A3 </F>
<F P=103> TA2806110194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv HA'ARETZ </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by political correspondent Aluf Ben] </F>
  [Excerpts] Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres has proposed 
incorporating Israel into NATO's Partnership for Peace in 
Europe. The proposal, included in a report Peres presented to 
the Knesset on his ministry's activities, says that the 
expansion of Israel's diplomatic ties includes joining 
organizations in which it has not held membership to date. 
  Peres raised the proposal in a conversation with U.S. 
Secretary of State Warren Christopher in Washington about a 
month ago, when he proposed that Israel, Jordan, and Egypt join 
the Partnership for Peace and form a dialogue with NATO on joint 
security problems as a start toward future regional security 
cooperation. [passage omitted] 
  A different Peres proposal was to include Israel in the CSCE 
and to establish a dialogue on security in the Mediterranean 
basin and on economic cooperation. The Foreign Ministry began 
contacts with the CSCE secretariat in Vienna, and according to 
the report presented to the Knesset, the Israeli initiative was 
welcomed by the organization's secretary general. 
  Foreign Ministry sources said yesterday that the proposal 
for 
inclusion in European security organizations were brought up as 
a basis for the new security regime Israel is proposing be set 
up in the Middle East. Peres had proposed that it be based on 
the existing European mechanisms initially, with a separate 
regional framework being set up later. 
  According to the sources, the Foreign Ministry top echelons 
now prefer to immediately set up a regional framework to be 
called the "Middle East CSCE," which would have three "baskets": 
security, economic cooperation, and human relations. 
  Peres proposed that the multilateral talks be used as the 
basis for setting up the organization, which would serve as a 
nucleus for a new system of relations between Middle East 
countries in the era of peace. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-38180 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes125_a_94001" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-125 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  28 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ARAB AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Algeria </F>
<H3> <TI>   Interior Minister Deplores Triumph of Extremism </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Interior Minister Deplores Triumph of Extremism </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2806231994 Algiers ENTV Television Network in Arabic 1900 
GMT 28 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2806231994 </F>
<F P=104>  Algiers ENTV Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] In Bordj Bou Arreridj Province, Abderrahmane 
Meziane Cherif, minister of interior, local authorities, 
environment, and administrative reform, attended the official 
installation of the governor today. He delivered a speech in 
which he outlined the government program in the transitional 
period. Over to Nourredine Daroui from Bordj Bou Arreridj: 
  [Daroui] In his meeting with officials and members of the 
public, the minister talked about the internal situation in the 
country in general. 
  [Begin Cherif recording] Regrettably, we notice that the 
spirit of factionalism and extremism has triumphed over wisdom 
and clear-sightedness. All Algerians have to overcome these 
beliefs that are so incompatible with the national interest and 
the spirit of fraternity and brotherliness which has enabled us, 
through the centuries, to preserve our personality with all its 
aspects. This is the spirit which led to the uprising of 
November [1954] and its intrinsic significance. [end recording] 
  [Daroui] The interior minister also talked about the 
importance and objectives of the transitional period in all 
fields within the framework of action aimed at bringing the 
country out of the stifling crisis it is going through. He said: 
  [Begin Cherif recording] The world is now watching, with 
astonishment, our acute disagreements and our confrontations and 
it is interfering in our affairs by supporting parties or 
deviant groups. Local and then legislative elections were held 
and democracy was nearly wiped out because some people regard it 
as blasphemy, while others see it as a means to remove others. 
Thus, we are now going through a transitional period which we 
hope will take us, once and for all, out of the contradictions 
and conflicts and lead us toward a bright future under 
democracy, the democracy which respects the country's ideals. 
[end recording] 
  [Daroui] Regarding the real perspectives for the future, the 
interior minister pointed out that the best alternative is 
action on the ground. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

