<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Northern, Southern Parties Hold First Talks in U.S. </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Northern, Southern Parties Hold First Talks in U.S. </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN2906055394 Paris Radio Monte Carlo in Arabic 0500 GMT 29 
Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN2906055394 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris Radio Monte Carlo </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] The two warring parties in Yemen have met in New 
York for the first time since the outbreak of the conflict. The 
northern party was represented by 'Abd-al-Karim al-Iryani 
[minister of planning and development] and the southern party 
was represented by Haydar Abu-Bakr al-'Attas [prime minister of 
the government declared in south Yemen]. The meeting was 
attended by the UN envoy to Yemen, Lakhdar Brahimi, who called 
on them to set a date for cease-fire. Al-Iryani, however, did 
not have full authorization from Sanaa to make such a decision, 
as Haydar Abu-Bakr al-'Attas said in his statements to reporters 
following the meeting. 
  The meeting was not in vain, because it brought closer the 
two sides' viewpoints on the formation of the committee which 
will supervise the cease-fire. REUTER cited Abu-Bakr al-'Attas 
as saying: We have almost reached an agreement on the Arab, 
African, and Asian countries which would participate in this 
committee. Al-Iryani suggested that both France and the United 
States participate in this committee. Both sides agreed -- 
through al-Iryani and al- 'Attas -- that the observers operate 
under the supervision of Lakhdar Brahimi with the assistance of 
a military attache. The obstacle, however, was represented in 
the southern party's insistence that the observers operate under 
the UN flag. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

