<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Source' Denies 'Abbas Intention To Quit Fatah </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Source' Denies 'Abbas Intention To Quit Fatah </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2806115894 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 26 Jun 94 p 5 </F>
<F P=103> PM2806115894 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Source Close to Abu-Mazin Denies He </F>
Intends To Resign From Fatah"] 
  [Text] Tunis, AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT -- While it has been 
confirmed that Muhammad Ghunaym (Abu-Mahir) has submitted his 
resignation from the Mobilization and Organization Department in 
Fatah and from his other political and movement duties, Fatah 
sources have told AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT that Mahmud 'Abbas 
(Abu-Mazin) is in severe disagreement with Palestinian President 
Yasir 'Arafat because of his hesitation over returning to Gaza 
and Jericho and offering guarantees to the World Bank and the 
donor states to facilitate the provision of grants and aid -- 
which prompted some people to talk about the possibility of 
Abu-Mazin's resigning his posts. But an authoritative source in 
the office of Abu-Mazin, head of the PLO Pan-Arab and 
International Relations, has stressed to AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT that 
"there is no truth in recent reports of Abu-Mazin's intention to 
quit political and organization action or to resign from Fatah." 
  The source added that Abu-Mazin's explaining the reasons 
that 
prompted Abu-Mahir to resign and to quit political and movement 
action does not mean "a similarity in their positions." The 
source vehemently denied that there is any coordination between 
Abu-Mahir and Abu-Mazin with regard to the resignation issue. 
  AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT has learned that Abu-Mazin and Faruq 
Qaddumi (Abu-al-Lutf) [head of the PLO Political Department] 
succeeded the day before yesterday in persuading Abu-Mahir to 
abandon his seclusion and resume his daily work in his office. 
Cadres from the Mobilization and Organization Department have 
contacted Abu-Mahir at his home, urging him to abandon his 
resignation "because he is needed in order not to perpetuate 
autocracy in the movement." 
  Elsewhere, AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT has learned that a 
misunderstanding arose yesterday between 'Arafat and Abu-al-Lutf 
in front of European Union ambassadors over the current balance 
of the Scandinavian states' aid fund for the Palestinian people 
-- the fund named after the late Norwegian Foreign Minister 
(Jorgen) Holst. Reports say that 'Arafat put the figure at $53 
million, while Abu-al-Lutf put it at $60 million. This conflict 
in the figures aroused the European ambassadors' suspicions 
about the fate of the $7 million, the difference between the two 
figures. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

