<F P=100> LEBANON </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hizballah Leader on Prisoner Exchange With Israel </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hizballah Leader on Prisoner Exchange With Israel </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2906103394 Kafr Killa Voice of the South in Arabic 0930 
GMT 29 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2906103394 </F>
<F P=104>  Kafr Killa Voice of the South </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] In an interview with the NATIONAL NEWS AGENCY, 
Hizballah Deputy Secretary General Shaykh Na'im Qasim answered a 
question on prisoner exchange with the Israelis. He said that 
in the past an international organization, the United Nations, 
intervened and sent a personal envoy--Gian Domenico Pico--to 
discuss the issue of POW's between the Lebanese and Israelis. 
He added: This effort stopped long ago and we consider that 
any neutral party acceptable to us, be it regional or 
international, is suitable to discuss the release of POW's held 
in Israel. 
  Qasim went on: We have said it before; we hold two prisoners 
and are ready to swap them with prisoners and detainees held in 
Israeli and South Lebanese Army jails but Israel is blocking 
this move. He noted that Mustafa al-Dirani's abduction has 
achieved nothing for Israel as regards airman Ron Arad. 
  Answering a question on Hizballah's view of the two 
indictments against [leader of the dissolved Lebanese Forces 
Party] Samir Ja'ja', he said: The measure was good and we call 
for strengthening the domestic arena to rally all resources in 
the face of Israel. 
  Assessing Hizballah's experiment in the Chamber of Deputies, 
he said parliament is a propaganda and political podium that 
contributes to supporting resistance and deals with problems in 
areas near the Israeli border. 
  The Hizballah deputy secretary general said the party has 
opened a dialogue with the Christians that is still in progress. 
He added that every Lebanese has the right to live in Lebanon 
and express his view quite freely. Should General Michel 'Awn, 
Raymond Iddih, or former President Amin al-Jumayyil decide to 
return to Lebanon, they would be returning to their homeland, he 
said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

