<H3> <TI>   Party Chiefs Confer With Iraqi Delegation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Party Chiefs Confer With Iraqi Delegation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN2906151994 Baghdad INA in Arabic 1420 GMT 29 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> JN2906151994 </F>
<F P=104>  Baghdad INA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Amman, 29 Jun (INA) -- 'Abd-al-Ghani 'Abd-al-Ghafur, 
member of the Iraq Command of the Arab Socialist Ba'th Party, 
has relayed the greetings of His Excellency President Saddam 
Husayn to Jordanian parties and the fraternal Jordanian people. 
'Abd-al-Ghafur also told the Jordanian parties that his 
excellency the president takes pride in the noble pan-Arab stand 
they took during the great showdown of the legendary Mother of 
Battles. 
  This came during a meeting between 'Abd-al-Ghani 
'Abd-al-Ghafur and the Arab Socialist Ba'th Party delegation on 
the one hand, and the secretaries general of 11 Jordanian 
parties in Amman today. 
  During this meeting, 'Abd-al-Ghafur reviewed the latest 
developments in the relationship between Iraq and the UN 
Security Council, as well as the efforts under way to lift the 
unfair sanctions clamped on Iraq. He indicated that the 
positive changes in the stands of most members of the UN 
Security Council are to be attributed to the steadfastness of 
the Iraqi people, and the wisdom of their leader Saddam Husayn. 
  'Abd-al-Ghani 'Abd-al-Ghafur urged nationalist, pan-Arab, 
and 
Islamic forces in Jordan and the Arab homeland to step up their 
efforts and activities prior to the next periodic review session 
of the UN Security Council in July. 
  During the meeting, the Ba'th Party delegation made some 
practical proposals regarding multifaceted moves that could be 
made on the pan-Arab and international scenes to expedite the 
lifting of the unfair sanctions and mitigate the sufferings of 
the steadfast Iraqi people. 
  For their part, the secretaries general of the Jordanian 
parties reiterated their total support for Iraq. They also 
commended its steadfastness in the face of the unfair embargo, 
as well as its legendary confrontation of all forms of 
aggression, conspiracies, and foreign intervention in its 
domestic affairs. 
  The Jordanian parties also renewed their full support for 
Iraq's unity, independence, and sovereignty, particularly since 
the battle it is waging is meant to vindicate Arabism and Islam. 
The enemy in this battle is one; namely, U.S. imperialism, and 
its ally, racist and expansionist Zionism, the Jordanian parties 
contended. 
  The conferees agreed to form a committee to draft practical 
proposals for future action on the Jordanian, Arab, and 
international scenes. 
  The meeting was attended by 'Abd-al-Razzaq al-Hashimi, 
director of the Foreign Relations Bureau of the Iraq Command of 
the Ba'th Party; Sa'd Qasim Hammudi, secretary general of the 
Arab Popular Forces Conference; and the Iraqi ambassador in 
Amman. 

</TEXT>

