Daily Report 
<DATE1>  27 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shakhray: Dudayev Can Normalize Russian-Chechen Ties </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shakhray: Dudayev Can Normalize Russian-Chechen Ties </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2705163994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1244 GMT 27 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2705163994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Lyudmila Yermakova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow May 26 TASS -- Russian Vice-Premier Sergey 
Shakhray does not rule out that the president of Chechnya "can 
become a political leader who would normalize relations with the 
Russian Federation." Talking to newsmen, Shakhray did not name 
the dates of the meeting between the leaders of Russia and 
Chechnya, but noted that such a meeting should be prepared. 
  Taking part in an all-Russia Conference on Federalism and 
Interethnic Relations, Shakhray emphasised that relations with 
Chechnya will be regulated on a negotiatory basis with bodies of 
power and all political forces, and will include free and fair 
democratic elections in the republic as a legal way out of the 
political crisis." 
  Shakhray said that the State Duma had accepted the Russian 
president's logic and has reproduced it in a resolution. The 
government has been directed to hold consultations with 
Chechnya's power bodies and political forces. The object of the 
consultations will be the draft treaty on the delimitation of 
subjects of control and authority. The treaty will be signed 
under the condition that Chechnya holds the elections, the 
deputy emphasised. 
  There is no other way to "overcome the decision adopted by 
the Fifth Congress of People's Deputies on the illegality of 
elections in Chechnya," according to Sergey Shakhray. At the 
same time, he explained that at the present, no ultimatum is 
being issued as to when and under what conditions the elections 
are to be held. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

