<H3> <TI>   Groznyy Warns Against Extension of `Regime' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Groznyy Warns Against Extension of `Regime' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3105130194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1153 GMT 31 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3105130194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Groznyy, will react "extremely negatively" if the 
Russian authorities extend the state of emergency to part of 
Malgobek and Sunzhen Regions in Ingushetia, Chechnya's 
presidential structures told Interfax on Tuesday. An official 
reaction will follow as soon as the decree signed by the Russian 
president on this score is "studied carefully enough." 
  The decree signed by Boris Yeltsin on Monday provides for 
the 
imposition of a special regime virtually throughout Malgobek and 
Sunzhen Regions in Ingushetia. These regions are disputed by 
Chechnya and Ingushetia, and Groznyy, views them as inherently 
Chechen territories. 
  As Chechnya's Foreign Ministry told Interfax, Groznyy, will 
view the deployment of Russian troops in Malgobek Region as an 
"aggression by a foreign country." Chechnya's Foreign Minister, 
Shamseddin Yusef, told Interfax that "adequate measures will be 
taken to rebuff an aggression by Russian troops." 
  In the meantime Interfax learned from military sources in 
Groznyy that on Wednesday Chechnya's armed forces are beginning 
military exercises. The exercises are to take place in the 
"territories bordering on adjoining states." Last week 
Chechnya's troops went on high alert in connection with the 
possible imposition of a state of emergency in Malgobek and 
Sunzhen Regions of Ingushetia by Moscow. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

