<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Meets With Tatar Factory Managers </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yeltsin Meets With Tatar Factory Managers </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3005191494 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1736 GMT 30 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3005191494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Russian government will make a list of 
potentially bankrupt factories, Russian President Boris Yeltsin 
said Monday when he met with the managers of the Kama automobile 
factory KamAZ in Naberezhnye Chelny during his tour of 
Tatarstan. Yeltsin explained that the list would include 
factories which could not be run profitably on their own and 
that it would be updated monthly. 
  He said that the decrees on tighter finances and production 
that he had signed earlier would be supplemented with four new 
decrees of the same kind. 
  He emphasized that the Russian economy, notably its 
manufacturing industries, needed faster restructuring. Because 
this was proceeding slowly, the payment crisis was getting 
worse, he said. 
  He promised that the state would help KamAz which was 
recovering from a fire. Foreign investments would be attracted 
to it and credits would be made available. Yeltsin said that 
KamAz was exempt from profit and value-added taxes until the end 
of the year. 

</TEXT>

