<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Radetskyy Sums Up Visit to NATO Headquarters </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Radetskyy Sums Up Visit to NATO Headquarters </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2905001994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1518 GMT 28 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2905001994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] On Saturday Ukrainian Defense Minister Vitaliy 
Radetskyy told newsmen in Kiev that security for Ukraine spelled 
overall security. Radetskyy summed up results of an official 
visit by a delegation of Ukrainian military to NATO's 
headquarters in Brussels. 
  According to Radetskyy, the participants in the Brussels 
meeting appreciated the Ukrainian stand on efforts to build a 
new system of security in Europe and approved principles on 
which Ukraine was to build its armed forces. 
  Everyone he met, Radetskyy said, supported, in no uncertain 
terms, the Ukrainian leaders who sought to preserve the 
territorial integrity of their country and insure the 
inviolability of the Ukrainian frontiers. 
  Radetskyy assigned priority to moves "to bridge the 
artificially-created gap between Ukraine and Europe and return 
Ukraine into the family of advanced European nations". 
  As a constituent part of Europe, Ukraine based its moves in 
the field of military politics on the principles of multilateral 
cooperation, Radetskyy said. 

</TEXT>

