<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   European Bodies Asked To Help Find Missing Rukh Leader </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    European Bodies Asked To Help Find Missing Rukh Leader </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU3005175194 Kiev DEMOKRATYCHNA UKRAYINA in Ukrainian 26 May 
94 p 2 </F>

<F P=103> AU3005175194 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev DEMOKRATYCHNA UKRAYINA </F>
<F P=105>  Ukrainian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [RUKH PRESS report: "The Case of Missing Mykhaylo </F>
Boychyshyn Has Become Internationally Known"] 
  [Text] Ukraine's People's Rukh [Movement for Perestroyka] 
appealed to parliaments of several countries and to the human 
rights organization "Amnesty International" with a request to 
help in the search for the deputy chairman of Rukh and head of 
its secretariat, Mykhaylo Boychyshyn, who disappeared without a 
trace. One of the deputies of the Swedish parliament, Peter 
Lyuksep, proposed that this affair be considered by the Swedish 
Parliament and also turned to parliamentarians of other European 
countries. The German Christian Democratic Union, the 
Conservative Party of Great Britain, the Conservative Party of 
Norway, the Liberal Party of Finland, and also the Human Rights 
Democratic Institute in Warsaw have already shown interest in 
the Boychyshyn affair. "Perhaps, the fact that Boychyshyn's 
case is becoming increasingly known in the international arena 
will compel law-enforcement bodies, which show total inactivity, 
to do something," a hopeful Vyacheslav Chornovil said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

