<H3> <TI>   Prime Minister Calls Black Sea Fleet Talks `Nervous' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Prime Minister Calls Black Sea Fleet Talks `Nervous' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2705150394 Kiev Radio Ukraine World Service in Ukrainian 
1300 GMT 27 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2705150394 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev Radio Ukraine World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Ukrainian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The second round of negotiations between government 
delegations of Russia and Ukraine on the problems of the Black 
Sea Fleet will begin in 10-15 days in the Ukrainian capital, 
acting Prime Minister of Ukraine Yukhym Zvyahilskyy told 
journalists upon his return from the meeting in Moscow. 
  Summing up the meeting, he said: "We did not win in Moscow, 
but neither did we lose. The talks were very nervous and tense." 
  "We were trying," he said, "to find options of positive 
solutions in fulfilling the tasks set by the president of 
Ukraine. We made concessions, but not those which would make 
Ukraine lose its wealth and independence." 
  Zvyahilskyy believes that a generally positive solution was 
found to the problem of separate deployment of the Black Sea 
Fleet and Ukraine's navy. Sevastopol will be the main Russian 
naval base in the Black Sea, while Ukraine's navy will be based 
in Balaklava and Donuzlav. 

</TEXT>

