<DOCNO> FBIS4-38352 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov104_e_94014" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-104 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  30 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Moroz: Ukraine Cannot Become Nuclear-Free `All at Once' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Moroz: Ukraine Cannot Become Nuclear-Free `All at Once' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3005152094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1252 GMT 30 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3005152094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ukraine cannot afford nuclear weapons, Aleksandr 
[Oleksandr] Moroz, the country's parliament chairman said in 
Kiev Monday. He added, however, that Ukraine was the sole 
country in the world that was gradually becoming nuclear-free. 
  Moroz said that Ukraine could not make this step all at 
once, 
no matter what kind of pressure was brought to bear on it. In 
his view, the West had to meet Ukraine half-way. The Western 
countries had to understand that investing in Ukrainian 
disarmament was not charity but payment for the security they 
enjoy as a result of Ukraine's moves. 
  Moroz admitted that he had once regarded the Black Sea Fleet 
as an element of collective defense forces. But now it was time 
to become aware of the fact that Ukraine and Russia had 
different interests in the Black Sea, meaning two friendly 
navies had to be set up. 
  He said that he would work for closer relations with Russia 
but thought that Ukraine's rejoining the ruble zone would do no 
good either to Ukraine or Russia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

