<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ambassador Says U.S. Has Pledged `Considerable' Aid </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ambassador Says U.S. Has Pledged `Considerable' Aid </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2905091594 Kiev Radio Ukraine World Service in Ukrainian 
0700 GMT 29 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2905091594 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev Radio Ukraine World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Ukrainian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ukraine has become the fourth country following 
Israel, Egypt, and Russia, which will receive considerable U.S. 
financial aid in the near future. Oleh Bilorus, Ukraine's 
ambassador to the United States of America declared this at a 
meeting with journalists. He pointed out that the Ukrainian 
Embassy in the United States managed to convince the U.S. 
Government that Ukraine requires aid today, when the first steps 
toward a market economy are being made. Bilorus underlined that 
President Bill Clinton's attitude toward Ukraine changed for the 
better and the United States of America was ready to support 
Ukraine politically and economically to consolidate its 
independence. 

</TEXT>

