<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kozyrev, Croatia's Granic Discuss Bosnia in Paris </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kozyrev, Croatia's Granic Discuss Bosnia in Paris </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2705162294 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1529 
GMT 27 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2705162294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Dmitriy Gorokhov, Andrey </F>
Krasnoshekov, and Andrey Shtorzh] 
  [Text] Paris, 27 May -- Russian Foreign Minister Andrey 
Kozyrev had talks with his Croatian counterpart Mate Granic 
during the international conference on stability in Europe that 
has been held here. The Russian minister told the ITAR-TASS 
correspondents today that the sides exchanged views on the 
prospects for an end to the conflict in Bosnia-Herzegovina, and 
analyzed the work of the Contact Group working on a Bosnian 
settlement, which has been meeting representatives of the 
warring sides in the French town of Talloires over the past few 
days. 
  "The work of the Contact Group is coming up against great 
difficulties, but everything is turning out reasonably well: 
Gratifyingly, we managed to get the Serb side to take part in 
the group's session," the minister pointed out. "Our western 
colleagues have also fulfilled the promises they made in Geneva 
in mid-May, and have got the Bosnian Muslims and Croats to the 
negotiating table." 
  Andrey Kozyrev said he had information that the Muslim and 
Croat sides are virtually ready to accept the plan proposed for 
the territorial division of Bosnia-Herzegovina. This plan 
allots 51 percent of the territory of Bosnia-Herzegovina to a 
Croat-Muslim federation, and 49 percent to the Bosnian Serbs. 

</TEXT>

