<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Differences Over Embassy Location Aggravate Ties </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Differences Over Embassy Location Aggravate Ties </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3005181794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1755 GMT 30 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3005181794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Vladimir Solntsev] </F>
  [Text] Moscow May 30 TASS -- Disagreements over the 
location of the Russian Embassy in Seoul have lately become one 
of the main irritants in relations between Russia and South 
Korea, Russian high- level sources said on the eve of South 
Korean President Kim Yong- Sam's official visit to Moscow 
beginning on June 1. 
  The sources said that the South Korean Embassy in Moscow is 
located in the prestigious quarters of the city in an excellent 
building, while the Russian diplomats have been provided with a 
building in a poor condition on the outskirts of the city. 
  Additionally, the South Korean authorities have confiscated, 
without ample enough grounds, according to the Russian side, the 
territory previously occupied by the Russian Embassy. "This 
question has a very disappointing side," a high-ranking Russian 
diplomat said. 
  After South Korea established diplomatic relations with 
China, the Russian officials recalled, China received the 
building of the former Taiwanese Embassy in the centre of Seoul 
without any problem. Vietnam was provided with the building 
previously occupied by South Vietnam and only Russia has been 
denied the right to the building which, officials said, had been 
its rightful property since the end of the 19th century. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

