<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kravchuk: Relations With Russia Linked to Crimea </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kravchuk: Relations With Russia Linked to Crimea </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2805182794 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1601 
GMT 28 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2805182794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Viktor Demidenko and Mikhail </F>
Melnik] 
  [Text] Kiev, 28 May -- The Crimean leadership's position 
will damage "Ukraine's goodneighborly relations with Russia, 
which have always been, and still are, the determining factor in 
spite of everything," Ukrainian President Leonid Kravchuk 
believes. The Ukrainian head of state said this at the end of 
his one-day visit to Chernobyl AES [nuclear power station] and 
to the power workers' town of Slavutich. "The leaders of the 
Crimean Republic say they want to be a bridge between Ukraine 
and Russia, but in fact they are laying a `mine' under this 
bridge," the president said. 
  Leonid Kravchuk believes that there are forces that are 
doing 
this consciously, and there are also those who are laying this 
`mine' because they can see no civilized way to resolve the 
problem" [no open quotation marks as received]. "They have an 
arsenal of rallies and slogans," he added. At the same time, 
the president voiced the hope that "common sense will prevail 
among those who are disregarding the laws and Constitution of 
Ukraine and the universally acknowledged principles of the world 
community." 
  The president thinks "no one has the right to cross over the 
`red' line in pursuit of ambitions. If anyone goes this far, we 
will take decisive and consistent action, but within the 
framework of the Constitution. There is no other way." There 
is only one way: To resolve all problems peacefully in 
accordance with the law, Leonid Kravchuk emphasized. 
  He also issued a warning to those who strive to achieve 
their 
own parochial interests. The president stressed: There are 
enough forces in Ukraine to neutralize those who "resort to 
unlawful actions." He stressed at the same time that he will 
not permit any infringement of the principles of goodneighborly 
relations with Russia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

