<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-104 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  30 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Crimea Refuses To Rescind Decision on Constitution </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Crimea Refuses To Rescind Decision on Constitution </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3005172794 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1538 
GMT 30 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD3005172794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS special correspondent Vladimir Gondusov] </F>
  [Text] Simferopol, 30 May -- Deputies of the Crimean 
Parliament have decided at the sittings of their commissions 
that there are no grounds for rescinding their decision on 
restoring the main points of the 1992 Constitution, which 
provides for setting up a Crimean statehood and building 
Crimea's relations with Ukraine on the basis of treaties. An 
ITAR-TASS correspondent learned this from Viktor Mezhak, deputy 
chairman of the Crimean Parliament. 
  Today is the deadline of the 10-day period during which, at 
the demand of the Ukrainian Parliament, the Crimean Supreme 
Council was to have brought the Crimean Constitution into 
agreement with the Ukrainian Constitution currently in force and 
with the law on the division of powers between the state power 
bodies of the two republics. 
  Mezhak said that common sense should prevail at the session 
of the Ukrainian Supreme Council, which is opening tomorrow [31 
May], and that the Ukrainian Parliament should not empower the 
president of Ukraine to "act stupidly" with regard to Crimea, as 
he called it. All the more so, he said, that not a single 
statement in the restored Constitution violates territorial 
integrity or leads to existing borders being redrawn because, 
under the Constitution, Crimea remains part of Ukraine. 
However, it would henceforth develop its relations with Ukraine 
on the basis of treaties and agreements through delegating power. 
  According to the deputy chairman of the Crimean Parliament, 
a 
working group is to be formed from deputies of the Ukrainian 
Supreme Council and it is to come to Sevastopol no later than 
Friday [3 June] in order to continue the talks previously held 
in Kiev. 
  Mezhak said the situation in Crimea is reasonably quiet and 
there are no grounds for concern. However, in his opinion, 
attempts to destabilize it from the outside depress people and 
introduce a note of anxiety into their everyday life and work. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

