<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kravchuk Decree on Reorganizing Crimea Security Illegal </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kravchuk Decree on Reorganizing Crimea Security Illegal </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2705172594 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1501 GMT 27 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2705172594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS special correspondent Sergey Karmalito] </F>
  [Text] Simferopol May 27 TASS -- The decree of Ukrainian 
President Leonid Kravchuk to reorganize the Crimean security 
service into the Ukrainian security service's main department in 
the Crimea and subordinate it directly to Kiev "is illegal in 
all respects," Chairman of the Crimean Security Service Vladimir 
Lepikhov told ITAR-TASS today. 
  In his opinion, the decree will not help to raise the 
efficiency of the department or ensure security of the 
law-governed democratic Crimean Republic. 
  Judging by official statements of the Ukrainian side, the 
Ukrainian Security Service does nothing to destabilize situation 
in the Crimea, said the service chairman. At the same time, 
movement of materiel and deployment of hospitals claimed by Kiev 
as an arrangement planned for the first half of the year run 
counter to the striving to preserve tranquility in the Crimea 
and give grounds to mass media for stirring up tension. The 
ongoing reinforcement of the Ukrainian National Guard units in 
the Crimea both with materiel and personnel does the same. 
  All these steps provoke concern of Crimean residents, 
parliament deputies and republican heads, said Lepikhov. It 
would be better to abstain from these actions or change their 
form, he added. 
  In the opinion of Lepikhov, the only civilized way out is 
boosted negotiations with the Crimea. The intensive dialogue 
should aim to settle disputable issues related to the restored 
validity of the Crimean Constitution of May 6, 1992, 
coordination of this decision with Ukraine at all levels, and 
conclusion of corresponding treaties and agreements and 
delegation of powers. All efforts should aim to reach a 
consensus, he stressed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

